00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
Welcome to our discussion about the base pipe operator in R version 4.1 and above.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:03.000
The base pipe operator was introduced in R version 4.1 as a native way to chain operations.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.000
It allows you to pass the result of one function directly as the first argument to the next function.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:14.000
This makes code more readable by avoiding nested function calls like traditional R syntax.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Unlike the magrittr pipe, the base pipe is built into R without requiring additional packages.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Let's look at some practical examples of using the base pipe operator in R.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Here's a simple example that takes a vector of numbers, filters those greater than 5, and calculates their mean.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:38.000
Here's a data frame example that selects rows where age is greater than 30, then extracts the name column.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
The underscore placeholder can be used.

