00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
about the art of vibe coding over those four weeks.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
And I'll split this into two buckets.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
One is reasons to vibe code more.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And then the other is caveats to consider.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:02.000
And here they are.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
Models improve fast.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Iteration is cheap.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
Apps are safer than stats.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
And then in terms of caveats, smaller is better.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.000
Security, security.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
And vibe coding is a bad name.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
So let's jump into some of those.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
The first is models improve fast.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
So this is kind of self-explanatory.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I think we really are still in the exponential phase of improvement of some of these coding models.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
Here is one example illustration of that.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:30.000
This is SuiteBench, which is a popular evaluation framework, software engineering bench,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
of large language models on their ability to solve open issues

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
on a range of open source repositories on GitHub.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And you can see that over one year, from August of last year to August of this year,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:48.000
the frontier models have gone from maybe 33% performance on this to about 75%.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
So learning software development much faster than I can.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
And so what was impossible a few months ago is now routine.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
And I have been checking in monthly or every few months to see, like,

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
at what point are the models getting good enough where they can actually build these things

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
that I've been dreaming of for me.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
And so I'd say to you as well, if you've been put off before,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:15.000
maybe you tried some AI coding tools and you found they were not good enough for your use cases,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
do retry now.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
The second is that iteration is cheap.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
Okay, so generations are quite fast.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
Models are non-deterministic, so you should retry often.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Many times you try out some coding problem and the first solution is bad,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
so you decide that the model is not capable of that kind of reasoning.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.000
But because you can generate many iterations very quickly,

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
I'd recommend that you just retry.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.000
In many cases, I would sort of going back and forth with the model,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:49.000
only get to a solution that worked on the 10th or 11th try.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
And to call out Positron Assistant,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
they recently added a way to restore your previous checkpoint.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Positron Assistant, by the way, is a great way to get into vibe coding.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And so after the model makes some mistake,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
you can just go back to your previous checkpoint and start again.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.000
And here's a prompt that I often use in a lot of my debugging with these AI tools,

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
is I have the model try to identify five possible causes of a specific bug,

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:21.000
and then code up a solution for those theoretical causes,

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
and then put each of them in a separate script,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
and then I go in and test each of those.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
So you can iterate very quickly this way and get to good outcomes.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And finally, apps are safer than stats.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
What I mean here is that it's easier to spot hallucinations

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.000
in software applications than in statistical code.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:43.000
So one reason why I was very skeptical about using these AI coding tools initially

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
is that they can write sort of bad code that you don't spot,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:52.000
and then your analysis is broken and you are in a mess because of this AI tool.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Here's two examples of obvious mistakes from a theoretical model.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
And you would imagine that the one on the left, I've now made the button red,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
is much easier to spot than the one on the right.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
I've now written the bootstrap code.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
But the mistakes are both pretty blatant.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
But one of those is much easier to spot.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
And so even if you haven't maybe,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
if you're not feeling confident enough in the models

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
to be coding up your statistical code,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
they could maybe be building simple apps for you.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.000
And so if you've been convinced,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
here is a sort of vibe coding starter pack of some types of software

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:33.000
and tools that you could use for this kind of AI-assisted development.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
One, of course, is Positron,

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.000
which is bringing in a lot of useful AI tooling at the moment.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
You could start deploying HTML pages to GitHub.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And here are some ideas of things you could build.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Interactive learning games.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
For example, at Graph Courses, we have many multiple-choice questions.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And Klaus also talked about having these interactive LearnR exercises.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
And you could try to vibe code those into sort of more fun games for students.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
Student work galleries as well.

