And here are some links.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
And I'll put those links as well at the end of the slide deck.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Okay, so those are some reasons to vibe code more.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
Now here are some caveats to consider.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
We'll go through each of them in turn.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
First is smaller is better.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And so early on in this vibe coding process,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
maybe when I had one to four files, less than 2,000 lines,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
I could ask very vague questions or vague requests

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
and get immediate correct responses from the models.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:50.000
But as the code base grew, you start to need to refer to specific files

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:55.000
and give very detailed specifications about what you want the models to do.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
And for mature repos, you will run into a high anguish index.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:04.000
So we had said that recording and debugging videos was a 50 on that index.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
Letting a model make changes unsupervised on your large code base

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.000
is off the charts.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:16.000
So as you get to large repos, these models really start to flounder.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And as one demonstration of the kinds of large repos,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
I wouldn't recommend you use models unsupervised on.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
Here's PyShiny, which is 1,600 files, about a million tokens.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So that wouldn't even fit into the context of the largest or the best models at the moment.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
Second is security security.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
So one area where hallucinations and mistakes are not obvious,

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
even in application development, is security.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So you can have very big security holes in your application.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:47.000
And if you vibe coded that, you will not know where those are.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
And this is known in the software development industry.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:56.000
There have been a few cases of folks who had big database holes,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:01.000
and there's questions about whether those were caused by the rise of vibe coding.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.000
And here's one example from my development of Chalk Talk.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:10.000
The models in their testing would often just put all our API routes as a public route,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
meaning anyone can just use up all of our credits,

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
and I would need to go in and fix that.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
So that's one demonstration of the security issue.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
So it still needs deep expertise,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:24.000
and this is one reason why maybe we haven't released or are not planning to too soon

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:28.000
release Chalk Talk as a sort of hosted platform that you can use yet

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:34.000
until we've had sort of deeper professional security consulting on that.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And then last and maybe most importantly, vibe coding is a bad name.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So it gives the impression that it's a very easy thing.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
It doesn't require any focus. You don't need to know any coding.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
But I say it still requires focus even to build fairly simple apps,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:52.000
and some one-on-one knowledge of web development will come in super handy.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
How am I on time?

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Okay.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
And then for substantial apps, models need a lot of guidance.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.000
So my real history is that I've done a lot of shiny development

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
and some web development massive open online courses as well,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
so I've learned a little bit of web stuff.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
And so you can tell from the kinds of prompts I'm using

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
when I'm communicating with these models,

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:18.000
lots of references to CSS and body tags and things of that sort.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:22.000
So again, like Klaus, I've been forced to learn CSS as part of my data science career.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
And there's lots of last-mile issues as well.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:29.000
The models are bad at finding docs, handling auth, and so on and so forth.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
Okay, so going back to the motivating questions from my talk,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
can I vibe code my dream application? I would say almost.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.000
If so, is there still a point? Is programming education still useful?

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And I would say definitely yes.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:42.000
Because even as we move to a world where most code is AI-generated,

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:45.000
you still kind of need to speak the language of code

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
to specify what you want to the models

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
and understand what you get out of those models.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:54.000
And there's always going to be many last-mile problems that still need humans.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:58.000
And as a quick analogy to that, should children learn arithmetic, one may wonder?

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:01.000
And I think most people would say yes.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:05.000
Because even in a world where we have calculators that can do mental arithmetic,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.000
you know, millions to billions of times faster than humans,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
you still need to speak the language of math

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:13.000
to specify what you want to these calculators

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
and to understand what you get out of them.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
And there's many math problems that still need humans

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:21.000
who then need the strong foundations, many of these last-mile problems.

